\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Quantum computing leverages the principles of quantum mechanics to process information in fundamentally new ways, offering exponential speed-ups for certain computational tasks. Unlike classical computers, which use bits as the smallest unit of data, quantum computers use quantum bits or qubits, which can exist in multiple states simultaneously. This property, known as superposition, along with entanglement, allows quantum computers to solve complex problems more efficiently. Applications include cryptography, optimization, and drug discovery. Companies like IBM, Google, and Microsoft are at the forefront of developing quantum computing technologies, which promise to revolutionize fields such as artificial intelligence, materials science, and financial modeling.}